PSY100H1-F-20205.courseDescription: A brief introductory survey of psychology as both a biological and social science. Topics will include physiological, learning, perceptual, motivational, cognitive, developmental, personality, abnormal, and social psychology.
PSY100H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online hybrid course.
Lectures will be given as video recordings (2 – 3 hours) once per week asynchronously. Virtual office hours sessions (3 hours) will be offered once per week via BB Collaborate (Wednesday 5 - 8 pm).
Tutorial sessions will also be offered on BB Collaborate at several points during the semester.
Some assessments in the course will be timed and completed on Quercus on specific dates.

PSY100H1-S-20205.courseDescription: A brief introductory survey of psychology as both a biological and social science. Topics will include physiological, learning, perceptual, motivational, cognitive, developmental, personality, abnormal, and social psychology.
PSY100H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online hybrid course. Lectures will be given as video recordings (2 – 3 hours) once per week asynchronously. 
Virtual office hours sessions (3 hours) will be offered once per week via BB Collaborate (Wednesday 5 - 8 pm). 
Tutorial sessions will also be offered on BB Collaborate at several points during the semester. 
Some assessments in the course will be timed and completed on Quercus on specific dates.

PSY201H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Fundamentals of descriptive and inferential statistics, including population and sampling distributions, simple association, probability, estimation, and hypothesis testing.
PSY201H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This will be an online hybrid course. Lectures will be available asynchronously for students to view at any time. Students will have the opportunity to ask questions and clarifications about class through the Quercus Discussion Board, email, or virtual office hours. Course assessments will be delivered synchronously during scheduled course times (Tuesday or Thursday from 6-9PM).

PSY201H1-S-20205.courseDescription: Fundamentals of descriptive and inferential statistics, including population and sampling distributions, simple association, probability, estimation, and hypothesis testing.
PSY201H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online hybrid course. Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online modules asynchronously. Students will be able to watch these lecture modules on their own time. There will be two lecture modules per week (total of about 6 hours of lecture time per week). Students will have the opportunity for synchronous virtual office hours with the instructor and TAs. Students will also be able to arrange virtual meetings outside of these times. Course assessments will be delivered somewhat synchronously whereby students will have 24 hours to complete tests and/or final assessments. During these types of assessments, the instructor and Tas will be available for questions for some of the hours in the day but availability will not be possible during the entire 24-hour period. Please note that all times for the course will be given in EST (i.e., Toronto time). Students need Word, PDF, Internet, and virtual access to the course textbook and practice questions for this course.

PSY202H1-S-20205.courseDescription: Fundamentals of statistical analysis of experimental and observational data including linear models, the analysis of variance, a priori contrasts, post-hoc tests, power analysis and effect size calculations.
PSY202H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, synchronous course.
Lectures will be given as 2-hour streams Tuesday and Thursday from 6:00 - 8:00 PM.
Tutorials will be 1 hour and will directly follow the lecture.
Students will access lecture and tutorials through Blackboard Collaborate.

PSY210H1-S-20205.courseDescription: The developmental approach to the study of behaviour with reference to sensorimotor skills, cognition, socialization, personality, and emotional behaviour.
PSY210H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is a hybrid, online course that will be delivered both asynchronously (pre-recorded videos) and synchronously (live webinars).
Weekly asynchronous lecture videos will be available online every Monday.
You will have the opportunity to ask questions and seek clarifications on lectures and course content via weekly synchronous 1-hour tutorials with TAs every Wednesday.
There will also be periodic synchronous sessions with the Course Instructor throughout the term.
Students will be required to use Microsoft Word, PowerPoint, Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra), and Quercus.

PSY220H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Contemporary areas of research in social psychology: social perception, attitudes, inter-personal relations, and group processes.
PSY220H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online, hybrid course. Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online videos/twice a week asynchronously. The midterms will be synchronous during class time. Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online webinar/office hours 2hrs/week (Monday and Thursday 2-3pm) to ask questions and clarifications about lecture and tutorial content. Students need Power Point and the ability to use Zoom.

PSY220H1-S-20205.courseDescription: Contemporary areas of research in social psychology: social perception, attitudes, inter-personal relations, and group processes.
PSY220H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online, hybrid course. Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online videos/twice a week asynchronously. The midterms will be synchronous during class time. Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online webinar/office hours 2hrs/week (Tuesday and Thursday 2-3pm) to ask questions and clarifications about lecture and tutorial content. Students need Power Point and the ability to use Zoom.

PSY240H1-S-20205.courseDescription: A critical survey of concepts, theories, and the state of research in the area of psychopathology and therapeutic methods.
PSY240H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
Lectures will be given as 2-hour online videos/week asynchronously and discussion will be completed on Quercus.
Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online office hours 3 times per week to ask questions and clarifications about course content.
Students need the ability to read and edit PDFs or PowerPoint slides and use Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra).
Tests will be timed and online.

PSY260H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Concepts, theories, and applications of classical and contemporary learning theories, including classical and operant conditioning. Current theories of the physiological and anatomical basis of learning and memory, including synaptic plasticity, the role of the hippocampus, amygdala, frontal cortex and other brain regions. Theories will be related to a practical understanding and applications such as drug addiction, phobias and other disorders.
PSY260H1-F-20205.prerequisite: PSY100H1/COG250Y1, OR registered in the Cognitive Science program
PSY260H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
Lectures and tutorials will be given as 2-3hr online files, 2 times/week, asynchronously.
Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online office hours Tuesdays (10-11am) and Thursdays (11am-12pm).
Students need Power Point and the ability to use Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra).

PSY270H1-S-20205.courseDescription: An introduction to research and theory on the neural and cognitive architecture of attention, memory, language, thinking and reasoning.
PSY270H1-S-20205.prerequisite: PSY100H1/COG250Y1, OR registered in the Cognitive Science program
PSY270H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online, asynchronous course.  Lectures will be given as a series of short videos totaling 2-3 hours/topic (4-6 hours/week) posted on Quercus.  Students will have the opportunity for a synchronous online office hour on Wednesdays from 2-3pm via MS Teams to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content.  Discussion boards will also be available to ask questions if students are unable to attend live office hours.  Students are expected to complete online homework via Top Hat each week.  Students need PowerPoint and Top Hat.

PSY290H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Provides students with a solid background into the biological basis of behaviour. Animal and human research topics include functional neuroanatomy, neural signalling, sensory and motor control, motivational systems, and hormones, and emotions.
PSY290H1-F-20205.prerequisite: PSY100H1/COG250Y1, OR registered in the Cognitive Science program
PSY290H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online hybrid course.
Lectures will be given as video recordings (2 – 3 hours) once per week asynchronously.
Virtual office hours sessions (3 hours) will be offered once per week via BB Collaborate (Monday 5 - 8 pm).
Some assessments in the course will be timed and completed on Quercus on specific dates.
Students will need a video player (that can play *.mov), pdf reader and the ability to use Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra).

PSY299Y1-Y-20205.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at http://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/course/rop. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PSY299Y1-Y-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Enrolment for the Research Opportunity Program is done by Arts and Science. For more information, please see: http://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/focus/course/rop

PSY313H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Age changes in sensory and perceptual processes, motor skill, learning, memory, and personality. Theory, methodological problems, social, cultural, and environmental influences that shape behaviour and attitudes towards and among the elderly.
PSY313H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online, asynchronous course.  Lectures will be given as a series of short videos totaling 2-3 hours/topic (4-6 hours/week) posted on Quercus.  Students will have the opportunity for a synchronous online office hour on Wednesdays from 2-3pm via MS Teams to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content.  Discussion boards will also be available to ask questions if students are unable to attend live office hours.  Students will also have the option of attending a live feedback conference about their written assignments with the instructor or TA via MS Teams.  Students are expected to collaborate with a small group of students to discuss important questions related to real-life applications of course material (provided by course instructor). This collaboration could be live or use Quercus discussion boards.  Students need PowerPoint and the ability to access an online textbook.

PSY322H1-F-20205.courseDescription:
An in-depth examination of theories and research in intergroup relations;
focuses on stereotyping, prejudice, discrimination, and stigma.
PSY322H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online modules asynchronously, including videos, quizzes, and other small lecture-related activities.
There will be two lecture modules per week (total of about 6 hours of lecture time per week).
Students will be able to attend the lectures synchronously on Tuesdays and Thursdays at 1-4pm if they wish to, however, these lectures will be posted and available for students to do on their own time in the modules.
Additionally, students will have the opportunity for synchronous virtual office hours with the course instructor on Tuesdays at 10am and Thursdays at 8pm to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content and assignments.
Students will also be able to arrange virtual meetings outside of these time with the course instructor and teaching assistants. Please note that all times are given in Eastern Time (i.e., Toronto time).
Students need Word, PDF, and Internet access for this course. We will be using various features in Quercus (including Bb Collaborate) as well as other free sites, such as Piktochart.

PSY323H1-S-20205.courseDescription: The effect of sex-role expectations on how men and women behave and perceive the world: theories of sex-role development, physiological and cultural determinants of sex differences, power relationships between men and women.

PSY328H1-F-20205.courseDescription: This course deals with psychological issues in the law, with particular reference to criminal law. It focuses mainly on research that has been done on pretrial publicity, eyewitness testimony, rules of evidence, and other factors that might affect jury decisions.
PSY328H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online, hybrid course. Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online videos/twice a week asynchronously. The midterm will be synchronous during class time. Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online webinar/office hours 2hrs/week (Monday and Thursday 3-4pm) to ask questions and clarifications about lecture and tutorial content. Students need Power Point and the ability to use Zoom.

PSY329H1-S-20205.courseDescription: Illustrates major methodologies within social psychology, such as attitude measurement, observation of small groups, and experiments. Course capacity is limited to 15 students and priority is given to PSY Specialists and Research Specialists during the first enrolment period.

PSY336H1-S-20205.courseDescription: A review of the field of positive psychology, which is the study of happiness and fulfillment. Topics include personal growth, meaning, hedonic and eudaimonic approaches to well-being, gratitude, awe, flow states, mindfulness and meditation.
PSY336H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, hybrid course. 
The course will consist of 4-6 hours of online lectures and videos that can be viewed asynchronously each week. 
Students can choose to listen to the lecture portion synchronously on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 12 noon - 2 pm if they desire. 
As part of this course students will also participate in small group discussions during some weeks. These will take place synchronously but will be scheduled based on group members' time zones and availability. 
Students will also can attend optional synchronous office hours on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 2pm - 3pm to ask questions or discuss course material. 
Students need the ability to use Canvas and Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra) including its audio (and ideally video) functions.

PSY343H1-S-20205.courseDescription: Examines various theories of how personality functioning may become impaired and corresponding psychotherapeutic interventions. Emphasis on empirical assessment of personality dysfunction and therapy effectiveness.
PSY343H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online hybrid course. Lectures will be posted as video recordings (2-3 hours) twice per week asynchronously (Tuesdays and Thursdays 5-8pm). Tutorial sessions will also be offered on BB Collaborate at several points during the semester (during class time - i.e., either on Tuesday or Thursday from 5-8pm) for review and clarification of lecture content. Tutorial sessions will be recorded and posted to Quercus, along with all other course materials. Virtual office hours sessions will be offered via BB Collaborate by request. Some assessments in the course will be timed and completed on Quercus during class time (Midterm assessment: Tuesday, July 23 at 5pm; Final assessment: Thursday, August 13 at 5pm).

PSY372H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Current theories and data on human memory: processes involved in encoding, storage, and retrieval.
PSY372H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online videos (broken up into shorter chunks) twice per week, asynchronously.
To help students keep up with and learn the material each week, there will be a mini-tasks (e.g., participate in a discussion board, submit a question for the webinar, complete a mini-quiz).
Students will also have the option to attend a synchronous online webinar session 1-4hrs/week to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content (Monday and Wednesday 6-7/8pm, depending on demand). This session will be recorded and posted for students who are unable to attend.
I will be available for office hours by appointment.
All readings including the textbook will be made available on Quercus.
Students will need access to a Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra) to attend the synchronous sessions.
In general, students will need access to a computer, reliable internet, and a quiet space. I understand that this can be a challenge in this unprecedented time, I encourage students to contact me immediately and directly if they are facing these challenges.

PSY396H1-S-20205.courseDescription: The functional relevance of neurotransmitters, with particular emphasis on their role in mediating behaviour.
PSY396H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, hybrid course.
Lectures will be given as 3hr online videos/week asynchronously.
Students will have the opportunity to participate in lecture synchronously (Mondays and Wednesday 6-9pm) to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content.
Students need Power Point and the ability to use Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra).

PSY399Y1-Y-20205.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at http://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/course/rop. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PSY399Y1-Y-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Enrolment for the Research Opportunity Program is done by Arts and Science. For more information, please see: http://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/focus/course/rop

PSY402H1-Y-20205.courseDescription: Examination in depth of specific topics in psychology at the graduate level. These seminars vary from year to year in terms of the number given, the topics, and the restrictions on enrolment. Students must get prior consent from the instructor of the graduate seminar they are interested in taking and submit this consent in writing to the department at which time you will be enrolled for undergraduate credit. Consult the Undergraduate Administrator for more details.
PSY402H1-Y-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online synchronous graduate course in Engineering open to 4th year PSY Specialists and Research Specialists from the University of Toronto only.
Permission must be given first by the instructor, Dr. Li Shu (shu@mie.utoronto.ca), and enrolment is done through the department by contacting undergrad@psych.utoronto.ca.

PSY405H1-Y-20205.courseDescription: An intensive laboratory or applied research project under the supervision of a Department of Psychology faculty member. Project must be academically demanding and uniquely suitable for the individual student. Additional information and applications are available at the department and on its website. This course is open to all Psychology program students.
PSY405H1-Y-20205.prerequisite: PSY202H1 (or exclusion), and appropriate background for the proposed work
PSY405H1-Y-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
For PSY405H1 and 406H1, 'E' indicator: students must first obtain consent of an instructor in the Department to supervise their project.
The proposal signed by student and supervisor should be submitted to the Undergraduate Administrator for approval (undergrad@psych.utoronto.ca) in Sid Smith, Room 4014, during regular academic advising office hours: Monday to Friday, 10:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

PSY406H1-Y-20205.courseDescription: An intensive laboratory or applied research project under the supervision of a Department of Psychology faculty member. Project must be academically demanding and uniquely suitable for the individual student. Additional information and applications are available at the department and on its website. This course is open to all Psychology program students.
PSY406H1-Y-20205.prerequisite: PSY202H1 (or exclusion), and appropriate background for the proposed work
PSY406H1-Y-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
For PSY405H1 and 406H1, 'E' indicator: students must first obtain consent of an instructor in the Department to supervise their project.
The proposal signed by student and supervisor should be submitted to the Undergraduate Administrator for approval (undergrad@psych.utoronto.ca) in Sid Smith, Room 4014, during regular academic advising office hours: Monday to Friday, 10:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

PSY424H1-F-20205.courseDescription: This lecture course focuses on the social psychology of interpersonal relationships between individuals, especially romantic or close relationships and friendships. It surveys what social psychologists have learned about the development, maintenance, disruption or dissolution of personal relationships, as well as current social psychological theories of interpersonal relationships.
PSY424H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
My plan is to do lectures live Mondays and Wednesdays at 1:00 EDT, but to record them and make them available to be viewed at any time.
If for some reason the live lectures turn out to be problematic, I will revert to simply recording lectures and posting them. However, ideally, I would to be able to do lectures with real time feedback and questions.
I will also host a weekly office hour. My plan is to hold that on a weeknight at 6:00 pm. However, I would appreciate feedback on the practicality of that time for your world region and can adjust it accordingly.
Students need PowerPoint and the ability to use Blackboard Collaborate.
Office hours will be held using Zoom.

PSY424H1-S-20205.courseDescription: This lecture course focuses on the social psychology of interpersonal relationships between individuals, especially romantic or close relationships and friendships. It surveys what social psychologists have learned about the development, maintenance, disruption or dissolution of personal relationships, as well as current social psychological theories of interpersonal relationships.
PSY424H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: This is an online hybrid course. Lectures will be given as video recordings (2–3 hours) twice per week asynchronously. Virtual office hours sessions (1 hour) will be offered twice per week via BB Collaborate (TBA). Some assessments in the course will be timed and completed on Quercus on specific dates.

PSY475H1-S-20205.courseDescription: This lecture course discusses visual attention; attentional selection for object recognition, feature integration, and action; attention in action-relevant space; movements of attention; eye-hand coordination, eye and limb movements; action-specific perception and effort-based models of perception; ecological perception and the perception of affordances.
PSY475H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online synchronous course.
Three-hour online lectures will be given twice weekly—Tuesdays and Thursdays 6PM to 9PM.
Students will need access to Blackboard Collaborate.

PSY493H1-S-20205.courseDescription: This is a capstone lecture course surveying research on how the mind arises from the brain. The first objective of the course is to understand how processes in human brains (ranging from the firing of a single neuron to the dynamics of billions) support cognitive abilities (such as recognizing a face, remembering a birthday from childhood, understanding the words in a spoken lecture, or planning a route home from class). The second objective of the course is to understand the methods of contemporary cognitive neuroscience research, to enable students to read primary literature and to understand ongoing debates.
PSY493H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online videos/week asynchronously.
Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online office hours upon request to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content and assignment marks.
Students need PowerPoint for lecture recordings and the ability to use Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra) for office hours.
All course material will be posted on Quercus/Canvas.

PSY494H1-F-20205.courseDescription: This lecture course discusses the role of brain and body in the expression and experience of emotion in humans considered through the experimental, physiological, theoretical, and clinical literatures.
PSY494H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions:
This is an online, asynchronous course.
Lectures will be given as 2-3hr online videos/week asynchronously.
Students will have the opportunity for synchronous online office hours upon request to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content and assignment marks.
Students need PowerPoint for lecture recordings and the ability to use Blackboard Collaborate (Ultra) for office hours.
All course material will be posted on Quercus/Canvas.
